data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11 (shipping with .NET 11), the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you had — likely `EnableSyncExecution()` in your `DbContext` options — no longer exists.

All four methods in your repository will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` all attempt synchronous execution against the Cosmos DB provider, which only has an async pipeline.

## How to fix it

Convert to async throughout:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory, no I/O.
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call chain).
- The relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) are **not** affected — they still support sync execution. This is Cosmos-specific.
